g and contrasting the "Jewish question" in France with discourses about women, blacks, and Native Americans, Schechter provocatively widens his inquiry, calling for a more historically precise approach to these important questions of difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aJewsxIdentityxFrance. 0aJewsxPublic opinion. 0aJewsxSocial conditionsx18th centuryxFrance. 0aJewszFrancexIdentity. 0aJewszFrancexSocial conditionsy18th century. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aacculturation.  aalienation.  aantisemitism.  aassimilation.  abelonging.  acitizenship.  acultural appropriation.  acultural theory.  adiscrimination.  aenlightenment.  aeurope.  aexile.  afeminism.  afrance.  afrench history.  afrench jews.  afrench revolution.  agender.  ahomeland.  ahuman nature.  aindigenous people.  aintolerance.  ajewish history.  ajewish population.  ajewish question.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  anational identity.  anative americans.  anonfiction.  aothering.  apolitics.  aprejudice.  aracism.  areligion.  areligious difference.  asocial body.  asocial issues.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092935740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929357423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929357/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  Univers